{{Infobox military person | honorific_prefix = | name = Charles School Blakely | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | nickname = | birth_date = {{birth date|1880|11|06}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1975|01|11|1880|11|06}} | death_place = | placeofburial = | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | allegiance = | branch = | serviceyears = | rank = [[Brigadier general]] | servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records --> | unit = | commands = | battles = | battles_label = | awards = | memorials = | spouse = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> | relations = | laterwork = | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | module = }} '''Charles School Blakely''' (November 6, 1880 â€“ January 11, 1975) was an American army officer and [[Brigadier general]] who served during [[World War I]].
== Early life == Blakely was born in [[Pennsylvania]]. In 1904, he graduated number twenty-nine of one hundred twenty-four from the [[United States Military Academy]]. Blakely's older brother, [[George Blakely (U.S. General)|George Blakely]], was also a graduate of the United States Military Academy, and a U.S. general. <ref>Davis, Henry Blaine. ''Generals in Khaki''. Raleigh, NC: Pentland Press, 1998. P. 39 ISBN 1571970886 {{OCLC|231779136}} </ref>
== Career == Blakely was an artilleryman, and was promoted to brigadier general on October 1, 1918, commanding an artillery brigade in France. After this, he was the Commanding General of the brigade fire center. From 1922 to 1925, he was executive officer for the Chief of Field Artillery in Washington. During 1926 and 1927, he studied at the Naval War College in [[Newport, Rhode Island]]. From 1934 to 1937, Blakely was assistant commandant of the Field Artillery School at [[Fort Sill, Oklahoma]]. In 1938, after thirty-four years of service, he retired due to disabilities.<ref>Davis, Henry Blaine. ''Generals in Khaki''. Raleigh, NC: Pentland Press, 1998. P. 39-40 ISBN 1571970886 {{OCLC|231779136}}</ref>
== Death and legacy == Charles School Blakely died at the age of ninety-four on January 11, 1975.<ref>Davis, Henry Blaine. ''Generals in Khaki''. Raleigh, NC: Pentland Press, 1998. P.40 ISBN 1571970886 {{OCLC|231779136}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=[Obituary]|work=The Courier-Journal|date=January 13, 1975|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=8}}</ref>
